WEBVTT

00:10.385 --> 00:14.346
[Woman]
♪ Those schoolgirl days ♪

00:14.431 --> 00:16.640
♪ Of telling tales ♪

00:16.725 --> 00:21.186
♪ And biting nails are gone ♪

00:22.897 --> 00:26.900
♪ But in my mind ♪

00:26.985 --> 00:29.611
♪ I know they will ♪

00:29.696 --> 00:35.284
♪ Still live on and on ♪

00:35.368 --> 00:38.495
♪ But how do you thank someone ♪

00:38.580 --> 00:43.625
♪ Who's taken you from crayons
to perfume? ♪

00:43.710 --> 00:46.045
♪ It isn't easy ♪

00:46.129 --> 00:50.716
♪ But I'll try ♪

00:50.800 --> 00:52.718
♪ If you wanted the sky ♪

00:52.802 --> 00:55.179
♪ I would write across the sky ♪

00:55.263 --> 00:57.181
♪ In letters ♪

00:57.265 --> 01:01.435
♪ That would soar
a thousand feet high ♪

01:01.519 --> 01:03.562
♪ To sir ♪

01:03.646 --> 01:07.441
♪ With love ♪

01:09.319 --> 01:13.197
♪ Those awkward years ♪

01:13.281 --> 01:15.449
♪ Have hurried by ♪

01:15.533 --> 01:21.038
♪ Why did they fly away? ♪

01:21.122 --> 01:26.126
♪ Why is it, sir ♪

01:26.211 --> 01:28.587
♪ Children grow up ♪

01:28.671 --> 01:34.134
♪ To be people one day? ♪

01:34.219 --> 01:37.304
♪ What takes the place
of climbing trees ♪

01:37.388 --> 01:42.518
♪ And dirty knees in the world outside? ♪

01:42.602 --> 01:44.770
♪ What is there for you ♪

01:44.854 --> 01:49.525
♪ I can buy? ♪

01:49.609 --> 01:51.527
♪ If you wanted the world ♪

01:51.611 --> 01:54.029
♪ I'd surround it with a wall ♪

01:54.114 --> 01:56.115
♪ I'd scrawl ♪

01:56.199 --> 02:00.369
♪ These words
with letters 10 feet tall ♪

02:00.453 --> 02:02.454
♪ To sir ♪

02:02.539 --> 02:06.959
♪ With love ♪♪

02:13.466 --> 02:16.468
Cor, my bleedin' feet.

02:16.553 --> 02:18.470
Oh, hello,
Mrs. Joseph.

02:18.555 --> 02:21.223
Oh, I like your hair.
What do you call that,
strawberry blonde?

02:21.307 --> 02:23.809
Go on.
You're only jealous.
[Laughing]

02:23.893 --> 02:26.145
Gert, whatcha got
for the old man's supper tonight?

02:26.229 --> 02:29.314
Him, he'll be lucky to get
faggots and peas pud,
he will.

02:29.399 --> 02:31.817
He can't do much
on that, can he, eh?

02:31.901 --> 02:34.278
[Both Laughing]

02:34.362 --> 02:37.072
All I want him for
is to keep me feet warm.

02:37.157 --> 02:39.575
- [Man] Tickets, please.
- Excuse me, dearie.

02:39.659 --> 02:42.161
Thank you.
Here, Gert. Wouldn't mind
having this little lot...

02:42.245 --> 02:45.956
in my stocking
for Christmas, eh?
[Gert Laughing]

02:46.040 --> 02:48.333
You wouldn't know
what to do with him.
You've been a widow too long.

02:48.418 --> 02:53.463
You speak for yourself.
It's like riding a bicycle.
You never forget how.

02:53.548 --> 02:56.175
[Women Laughing]

02:56.259 --> 02:59.386
I tell you what I'll do.
I'll send my Alfie along to you.

02:59.470 --> 03:03.515
- He's not bad once he gets going.
- Well, I hope he's well sprung.

03:03.600 --> 03:05.642
[Women Laughing]

03:14.110 --> 03:17.070
[Children Chattering]

03:41.304 --> 03:44.264
[Toilet Flushing]

03:50.146 --> 03:51.980
Morning.

03:53.066 --> 03:54.608
Looking for someone, mate?

03:56.152 --> 03:57.486
Nope.

03:59.155 --> 04:00.656
Nice day, isn't it?

04:17.548 --> 04:20.509
[Distant Chatter,
Laughter]

04:31.437 --> 04:34.356
[Chatter, Laughter
Grow Louder]

04:40.863 --> 04:44.199
Oh! Sorry.

04:49.539 --> 04:51.456
[Door Closes]

04:56.379 --> 04:58.297
Hackman's
in the staff room.

04:58.381 --> 05:00.507
Where he bleedin' well belongs.
Yeah.

05:00.591 --> 05:03.552
[All Shouting]

05:05.555 --> 05:08.557
[Chatter, Laughter
Continue]

05:17.984 --> 05:19.901
[Door Closes]

05:20.653 --> 05:22.154
Good morning.

05:23.573 --> 05:26.199
My name is Thackeray.
I'm a new teacher.

05:27.076 --> 05:30.203
Yes. We were expecting you.

05:30.288 --> 05:34.082
So you're the new lamb
for the slaughter.

05:34.167 --> 05:37.169
Or should I say "black sheep"?

05:37.253 --> 05:39.838
No, just a teacher,
Mr. Hackman.

05:39.922 --> 05:43.133
I'm not Hackman.
Perish the thought.

05:43.217 --> 05:45.886
He's departed.
God rest his soul.

05:45.970 --> 05:49.765
He's probably
pouring out his woes to
the divisional officer by now.

05:49.849 --> 05:51.767
Oh.
Oh. Weston.

05:53.436 --> 05:56.521
I'm Mrs. Evans.
Grace. Deputy head.

05:56.606 --> 05:57.939
Mrs. Evans.

05:58.024 --> 05:59.524
Have you seen
any of the children yet?

05:59.609 --> 06:03.153
I looked in on
Mr. Hackman's class for a moment.
Hmm.

06:03.237 --> 06:06.365
I take them for domestic science.

06:06.449 --> 06:09.034
[Chuckles]
Like a cup of tea?

06:09.118 --> 06:12.079
No. No, thank you.
Not just now.

06:13.623 --> 06:15.665
You been teaching long?

06:15.750 --> 06:17.709
This is
my first appointment.

06:17.794 --> 06:20.379
[Chuckles]
We call them jobs.

06:20.463 --> 06:22.881
American, are you?
British.

06:22.965 --> 06:26.426
From British Guiana.
But I've spent some years
in the States.

06:26.511 --> 06:29.054
Oh. Where?
In California.

06:29.138 --> 06:31.515
Oh. Weather as good
as they say?

06:31.599 --> 06:33.517
It's better.
[Chuckles]

06:35.728 --> 06:38.605
Uh, what was your subject?

06:38.689 --> 06:41.566
What did you major in?

06:41.651 --> 06:44.736
Engineering.
Oh!

06:44.821 --> 06:47.697
Well, uh, I must be off.

06:47.782 --> 06:51.535
Make yourself at home.
Wander around if you like or stay here.

06:51.619 --> 06:53.745
I'll introduce you to the others at lunch.

06:53.830 --> 06:55.789
Thank you.

07:15.351 --> 07:17.102
[School Bell Ringing]

07:21.107 --> 07:24.025
[Ringing Stops]
[All Chattering]

07:33.369 --> 07:35.787
This is Gillian, Mr. Thackeray.

07:35.872 --> 07:38.081
[Door Closes]
Gillian Blanchard.

07:38.166 --> 07:40.083
Hello.
How do you do?

07:40.168 --> 07:44.963
She's new here too.
Came the day before yesterday.
Tea, Gillian?

07:45.047 --> 07:46.965
Thank you.
[Door Opens]

07:47.049 --> 07:49.968
[Chattering]

07:50.052 --> 07:52.762
This is Mr. Mark Thackeray,
the new replacement.

07:52.847 --> 07:55.390
How do you do?
Josie Dawes,
Euphemia Phillips.

07:55.475 --> 07:57.434
They teach the little ones.

07:57.518 --> 08:00.687
Theo Weston you know.
Yes,
I've had the pleasure.

08:00.771 --> 08:03.190
He mistook me for Hackman.
I heard
he's fled.

08:03.274 --> 08:06.401
I can't say I blame him.
That shower of humanity is
enough to destroy anybody.

08:06.486 --> 08:08.403
He got what
he deserved.

08:08.488 --> 08:10.405
I'm Clinty Clintridge.
How are you?

08:10.490 --> 08:14.868
Clinty's a marvelous artist.
Got one into the Royal Academy
a couple of years ago.

08:14.952 --> 08:17.078
Teaching provides
the bread and butter.

08:17.163 --> 08:22.125
That's all the staff,
except for Mr. Bell,
our PT instructor.

08:22.210 --> 08:24.127
Well, I do hope you're
going to stay with us.

08:24.212 --> 08:26.963
I shouldn't if I were you, old man.

08:27.048 --> 08:32.177
- I should row home
while you've a chance.
- Don't discourage him, Weston.

08:32.260 --> 08:34.261
Well, I must go.

08:34.347 --> 08:37.682
I have to fix a bath for one
of the girls in Clinty's class.
Why?

08:37.767 --> 08:40.684
Oh, the kids
are complaining again.
Won't sit near her.

08:40.770 --> 08:44.022
[Thackeray]
What's the matter?
Personal hygiene problems.

08:44.106 --> 08:46.525
Fourteen and helpless.

08:46.609 --> 08:48.568
You men are lucky.

08:48.653 --> 08:52.155
The things we women
have to do for these kids.

08:52.240 --> 08:56.618
Gillian dear,
encourage him to stay.

09:02.083 --> 09:05.001
[Whispers]
Why is it everyone thinks
I need encouraging?

09:05.086 --> 09:07.295
[Whispers]
They said the same to me.

09:07.380 --> 09:11.716
There's something frightening
but at the same time challenging
about this school.

09:11.801 --> 09:13.885
Do you know there's no form
of corporal punishment?

09:13.970 --> 09:15.887
Or any punishment,
for that matter?
None?

09:15.972 --> 09:19.558
No. And I've no real
teaching experience,
so I'm a little lost.

09:19.642 --> 09:21.726
Well, I don't have
any experience either.

09:21.811 --> 09:25.522
Oh. Oh, well, of course
it'll be much easier for you.

09:25.606 --> 09:28.483
I'm a little afraid of them.
♪♪ [Rock]

09:28.568 --> 09:30.694
Midday dance session.

09:30.778 --> 09:32.904
During lunch break
the older kids use the hall.

09:32.989 --> 09:37.200
I sometimes join them.
Even the old man
shakes a leg on occasions.

09:37.285 --> 09:39.202
Dancing is merely their way
of keeping fit...

09:39.287 --> 09:43.248
for the more exciting pastime
of teacher baiting.

09:43.332 --> 09:45.750
Couldn't you manage to be
a bit less discouraging?

09:45.835 --> 09:48.587
It's the last thing
I want to do.

09:48.671 --> 09:50.589
The music's louder
than usual.

09:50.673 --> 09:54.718
They're probably celebrating
their victory over Hackman.

09:54.802 --> 09:57.053
I'd better go
and see Mr. Florian.

09:57.138 --> 09:59.097
I'll show you the way.

09:59.181 --> 10:01.349
[Woman]
♪ I gotta find out ♪

10:04.770 --> 10:08.481
♪ I just wish I knew ♪

10:11.611 --> 10:13.695
♪ Somebody help me
I just gotta know ♪

10:15.656 --> 10:18.366
♪ What is the cause
that started this round? ♪

10:19.535 --> 10:23.705
♪ I wish I knew who it could be ♪

10:23.789 --> 10:28.001
♪ I've gotta find out
because it's torturin' me ♪

10:28.085 --> 10:30.086
♪ I gotta find out ♪

10:30.171 --> 10:32.589
♪ Uh-huh ♪

10:32.673 --> 10:35.634
♪ I just wish I knew ♪
They're good, aren't they?

10:35.718 --> 10:38.970
- I suppose so.
- ♪ Who it could be ♪

10:39.055 --> 10:42.057
- ♪ I've gotta find out ♪
- The head's study is this way.

10:42.141 --> 10:44.726
♪ Because it's torturin' me
I've gotta find out ♪

10:44.810 --> 10:46.978
♪ I ♪
♪♪ [Stops]

10:47.063 --> 10:50.440
Um, do you two‒

10:50.524 --> 10:52.734
[Boy]
Don't know. Never had it.
[Laughter]

10:52.818 --> 10:55.153
Do you two shake?

10:55.237 --> 10:58.573
Um, well, I'll, uh,
see you later, Mr. Thackeray.

10:58.658 --> 11:00.575
[Girl]
Well?

11:04.497 --> 11:08.792
I, uh‒ Thank you,
but I have to go and see the principal.

11:08.876 --> 11:10.794
[Students Laughing]

11:17.259 --> 11:19.761
♪♪ [Resumes]

11:19.845 --> 11:22.889
♪ I just wish I knew ♪♪

11:25.559 --> 11:28.395
[Man]
You've excellent qualifications,
Mr. Thackeray.

11:28.479 --> 11:31.648
Astonishing ones, in fact...
as a communications engineer.

11:31.732 --> 11:36.444
Field experience in South American‒
Why do you want to be a teacher?

11:36.529 --> 11:38.530
Reasons.

11:38.614 --> 11:40.990
You've already tried
to get an engineering post?

11:41.075 --> 11:42.867
I've tried for 18 months now.

11:42.952 --> 11:44.953
Mm-hmm.

11:46.747 --> 11:49.499
We have no blueprint
in North Quay.

11:49.583 --> 11:52.627
Most of our children
are rejects from other schools.

11:52.712 --> 11:54.629
We have to help them
as best we can.

11:54.714 --> 11:57.757
We have to teach them what we can
and as much as we can.

11:57.842 --> 12:01.010
The local authorities
are not totally on our side.

12:01.095 --> 12:03.596
And from the moment
you accept this position,

12:03.681 --> 12:05.640
you'll be entirely
on your own.

12:05.725 --> 12:08.852
Of course, I and the staff
will do everything we can to help you,

12:08.936 --> 12:12.397
but success or failure
will depend entirely upon you.

12:13.733 --> 12:16.317
- Now, what's it to be?
- I want the job, sir.

12:17.987 --> 12:20.488
Good. Then it's settled.

12:20.573 --> 12:23.450
Now, tomorrow you'll
take over Hackman's class.

12:23.534 --> 12:25.452
[Thackeray]
Sapiano.
Yeah!

12:25.536 --> 12:28.079
Wong.
Yes.

12:28.164 --> 12:30.081
Osgood.
Yeah.

12:30.166 --> 12:32.083
Tuffen.
Yeah.

12:32.168 --> 12:34.085
Pegg.

12:34.170 --> 12:36.254
Pegg?
Yeah.

12:38.674 --> 12:40.592
Joseph.
Yeah.

12:40.676 --> 12:42.635
Dare.
Yeah.

12:44.513 --> 12:48.141
Potter. Potter!
Yeah.

12:48.225 --> 12:50.351
Denham.
Hmm.

12:52.438 --> 12:54.606
Buckley.
Yeah.

12:54.690 --> 12:56.941
Purcell.
Hmm.

12:58.027 --> 12:59.986
Fernman.
Yeah.

13:00.070 --> 13:02.530
Jackson.
Yeah.

13:02.615 --> 13:05.116
Strong.
Yeah.

13:05.201 --> 13:07.368
Seales.

13:07.453 --> 13:10.038
Seales!
Yeah.

13:10.122 --> 13:12.957
Palmer.
[Palmer]
Yes, guv'nor.

13:13.042 --> 13:15.251
Campbell.
Present.

13:18.464 --> 13:21.633
I don't know how much you know,
so we'll start from scratch.

13:21.717 --> 13:23.760
First, as I call your name,

13:23.844 --> 13:28.056
will you please read anything you like
from one of your school books.

13:29.475 --> 13:32.060
- Fernman.
- Right.

13:34.605 --> 13:38.441
"Only those who..."
"Arrived."

13:38.526 --> 13:42.779
"arrived on horseback...

13:42.863 --> 13:46.950
or in a public coach..."
[Thackeray]
Thank you.

13:48.035 --> 13:49.369
Denham.

13:56.168 --> 14:00.129
"If 14 hens lay an egg a day
for 30 days,

14:00.214 --> 14:03.925
how much are the eggs a dozen,
and how many have you to sell?"

14:04.009 --> 14:06.511
[Laughter]
Moira Joseph.

14:08.764 --> 14:12.225
"Pete Gilroy's weight
and the ever-tightening 'noosie'...

14:12.309 --> 14:14.227
about her neck..."
[Boy]
That's nice. Cor.

14:14.311 --> 14:16.855
"about her neck
began slightly...

14:16.939 --> 14:19.607
to 'impeddie'
the wild mare's speed.

14:19.692 --> 14:23.653
But Pete was only too fully aware
of what his fate would be,

14:23.737 --> 14:28.116
for he could not hope
to escape death from being
battered and crushed."

14:31.537 --> 14:33.496
Put that away, please.

14:35.249 --> 14:38.042
[Squeaks]

14:39.920 --> 14:42.297
[Toy Squeaks]

14:42.381 --> 14:43.756
Thank you.

14:55.144 --> 14:57.854
[Scattered Chuckling]

14:57.938 --> 14:59.856
Is there anyone else
who would like to read?

15:02.318 --> 15:04.319
Your name, please?
Pamela Dare.

15:06.322 --> 15:09.699
"And he had learned to love.
I know not why.

15:09.783 --> 15:12.577
For this in such as him
seems strange of mood.

15:12.661 --> 15:16.372
But thus it was.
And though in solitude,

15:16.457 --> 15:20.126
small power that nipped
affections have to grow.

15:20.210 --> 15:24.839
And in this glowed
when all beside had ceased to glow."

15:29.428 --> 15:31.346
Well done!
[All Cheering]

15:32.681 --> 15:34.641
[Cheering Continues]

15:38.604 --> 15:42.357
Thank you, Miss Dare.
Next: weights and measures.

15:42.441 --> 15:44.359
What's "avoirdupois"?

15:44.443 --> 15:46.569
"Avoirdu" what?
Avoirdupois.

15:46.654 --> 15:49.614
- Weights.
- Oh, yeah.

15:49.698 --> 15:52.951
Uh, heavyweight,
light-heavy, cruiser weight,

15:53.035 --> 15:56.079
middle, light, bantam,
fly, featherweight.

15:56.163 --> 15:58.289
[Boy]
Hey!
Thank you very much.

15:58.374 --> 16:00.416
[Cheering, Laughing]

16:02.795 --> 16:05.630
It's encouraging
that you have a sense of humor.

16:05.714 --> 16:10.009
It seems you know so little
and are so easily amused,

16:10.094 --> 16:12.095
I can look forward
to a very happy time.

16:13.430 --> 16:16.599
Now, copy down
the following tables.

16:18.060 --> 16:21.604
[Murmuring]
Who does he think he is,
the cheeky devil.

16:29.905 --> 16:32.824
[Tapping]

16:41.834 --> 16:43.751
Hello, Ducks.
Hello.

16:43.836 --> 16:46.004
[Chuckles]
Thought you might need this.

16:47.089 --> 16:49.007
Thank you.
How'd it go?

16:49.091 --> 16:53.094
Well, let's just say
the battle was joined.

16:56.390 --> 17:00.935
Ahh! I don't know what we'd do
without a cup of-

17:01.020 --> 17:03.062
What's your name?
Thackeray.

17:03.147 --> 17:05.189
I know that.
I mean your other name.

17:05.273 --> 17:07.525
Mark.
Mark.

17:07.608 --> 17:09.861
A couple of things, Mark.

17:09.944 --> 17:12.363
We all know the old man's views.

17:12.448 --> 17:14.866
Basically, we agree with them.

17:14.950 --> 17:16.742
But he's safe in an office.

17:17.953 --> 17:21.622
Now, these kids come from homes
where an order is usually
accompanied by a blow.

17:21.707 --> 17:25.542
One rude word to their parents,
the roof'll hit 'em.

17:25.627 --> 17:28.378
There's nothing like that
going on here, right?

17:29.506 --> 17:32.967
So they've got us
at a great disadvantage.

17:35.471 --> 17:39.557
Hackman tried to be popular.
He hung himself.

17:39.641 --> 17:43.144
Weston couldn't
care less about them.
Well, that's no good.

17:44.938 --> 17:47.273
[Sighs]

17:47.357 --> 17:49.317
I can't guide you, but...

17:51.070 --> 17:53.988
don't take any nonsense
from these little tykes.

17:55.741 --> 17:58.284
They're good kids, Mark.
Most of them.

18:00.204 --> 18:04.499
But if you don't solve them,
they'll break you, and damned quickly.

18:04.583 --> 18:07.752
That's been tried...
by experts.

18:08.837 --> 18:11.089
They're very expert.

18:11.173 --> 18:13.216
Please, can I leave
the room, guv?

18:15.010 --> 18:17.595
Yes. And it's "Thackeray."

18:17.679 --> 18:20.181
Oh. Yes, guv.
[Laughter]

18:26.855 --> 18:30.399
Now, most of you girls
help your mothers
with the shopping.

18:32.444 --> 18:35.988
So sorry, Mr. Thackeray.
Proper drafty in these parts,
isn't it?

18:36.073 --> 18:38.574
[Laughter]

18:39.660 --> 18:41.577
About multiplying.

18:41.662 --> 18:45.123
There are a few valuable
tricks to know.

18:45.207 --> 18:49.919
Say that you're offered roast beef
at seven shillings per pound.

18:50.003 --> 18:53.631
Potter! Must you do that?

18:53.715 --> 18:56.384
I can't help it, sir.
It's me desk.

18:56.468 --> 18:59.387
Aw, poor old Potts.
[All Chattering]

19:00.722 --> 19:03.891
Blimey,
did it make a noise?

19:06.311 --> 19:08.521
[Chattering Continues]

19:10.149 --> 19:12.066
[Thackeray Clapping]

19:15.904 --> 19:17.446
Sit down.

19:19.032 --> 19:21.951
[Murmuring]

19:28.750 --> 19:31.794
I'll speak with the caretaker
about it after school.

19:31.879 --> 19:34.964
[All Chattering]
Aw, isn't that nice?
Lovely.

19:36.592 --> 19:39.093
I hope I didn't miss nothing.
Where was he, Pam, love?

19:39.178 --> 19:42.096
Oh, yeah. About shopping
or something, wasn't it?
That's enough, Denham.

19:42.181 --> 19:44.098
Well, I was only asking,
Mr. Thackeray.

19:44.183 --> 19:46.184
Don't wanna miss nothing,
now, do I?

19:46.268 --> 19:50.605
Hey, Bert,
he was just about to show us
a new, invaluable trick.

19:50.689 --> 19:52.607
Oh, yeah.
When you're shopping,
well, you see‒

19:52.691 --> 19:56.402
I said, that's enough.
Sit down.

20:07.289 --> 20:09.540
Do exercise four, five and six.

20:09.625 --> 20:12.543
[Chattering In Protest]

20:20.677 --> 20:22.637
Very quietly.

20:25.224 --> 20:29.227
Don't worry.
The worst is still to come.

20:29.311 --> 20:32.521
You're still getting
what's known as
the "silent treatment."

20:32.606 --> 20:34.899
What's the next phase?

20:34.983 --> 20:38.694
Well, unless you can work up
a little black magic,

20:38.779 --> 20:42.406
these little bastards
have a multitude of tricks.

20:46.328 --> 20:47.703
Why did you take up teaching?

20:49.498 --> 20:52.416
Oh, it's good to have
some kind of a job.

20:54.253 --> 20:57.463
But I'm teaching them nothin'.
[Clucks Tongue]

20:57.547 --> 21:00.174
- I'm not even getting to first base.
- [Gillian] Don't worry.

21:00.259 --> 21:03.719
Your lot'll be leaving this term.
The next lot will be better.

21:03.804 --> 21:06.347
They'll be just as bad.
Probably worse.

21:06.431 --> 21:08.599
Then what's your answer?

21:08.684 --> 21:12.561
What they need
is a bloody good hiding.

21:15.482 --> 21:17.525
I feel rather sorry
for them, you know?

21:17.609 --> 21:21.362
I mean, most of them
can hardly read.

21:21.446 --> 21:26.575
You're so naive,
my dear old colleague.

21:26.660 --> 21:31.622
They'll be earning
twice as much as us
before you can shake a stick.

21:31.707 --> 21:35.835
They'll happily be part of
the great London unwashed‒

21:35.919 --> 21:41.465
illiterate,
smelly and quite content.

21:41.550 --> 21:44.427
An education's a disadvantage
in this day and age.

21:46.013 --> 21:49.515
That is ridiculous.
[Weston]
But still true.

21:50.642 --> 21:53.894
So you had better start
brushing up on your voodoo...

21:53.979 --> 21:56.063
if you wish
to remain sane.

22:02.988 --> 22:05.906
Good morning.
[All Chattering]

22:07.075 --> 22:09.035
All right.
Take your seats.

22:12.247 --> 22:15.333
Ooh!
All right, sir?

22:15.417 --> 22:18.169
I hope you didn't
hurt yourself, sir.
Ooh, are you all right?

22:18.253 --> 22:21.255
Gee, cheap stuff
they're sellin' nowadays.

22:22.799 --> 22:24.675
Want me to help, sir?

22:24.760 --> 22:27.762
[Students Murmuring]

22:57.959 --> 22:59.877
[Quietly]
Sit down.

23:24.528 --> 23:27.238
Take your proper places.

23:27.322 --> 23:31.534
Here, we can move around
here, you know, sir.
[Chattering In Agreement]

23:33.203 --> 23:35.996
Take your proper places.

23:39.668 --> 23:42.670
[Disappointed Chattering]

23:47.092 --> 23:48.759
Here, don't go climbin'
all over the seats.

23:48.844 --> 23:52.054
Don't behave
like a monkey.

23:52.139 --> 23:55.057
[Chattering Continues]

23:57.352 --> 23:59.603
Lads, come on.
Sit down.

23:59.688 --> 24:01.647
Keep quiet.

24:07.529 --> 24:09.655
[Yawns Loudly]

24:09.739 --> 24:12.283
Beg your pardon.

24:12.367 --> 24:15.327
[Metal Clattering]

24:23.712 --> 24:25.296
Something the matter, Seales?

24:26.715 --> 24:29.258
Seales,
is something wrong?

24:30.552 --> 24:33.137
It's me mum.
She's awful sick.

24:33.221 --> 24:36.098
Oh, I'm sorry.

24:36.183 --> 24:38.225
Anything I can do?

24:38.310 --> 24:40.227
No, nothing.

24:41.313 --> 24:44.315
She's English.
I see.

24:44.399 --> 24:47.526
You're like my old man,
excepting you're bigger and younger.

24:47.611 --> 24:50.946
Rotten bastard.
You shouldn't speak
like that about your father.

24:51.031 --> 24:55.326
You know nothing. I hate him!
Hate him! Why not, eh?

24:55.410 --> 24:59.163
I'll never forgive him
for what he did to me mum. Never!

24:59.247 --> 25:01.665
Well, he married her,
didn't he? Didn't he?

25:04.544 --> 25:07.463
[Train Passing]

25:22.103 --> 25:25.147
[Thackeray]
Today let's take a look
at South America.

25:26.525 --> 25:29.276
Oh, I'm sorry,
Mr. "Fackery."

25:29.361 --> 25:31.278
The bloody things just slipped.

25:31.363 --> 25:33.614
The name is "Thackeray."

25:33.698 --> 25:35.824
And they're not bloody things.

25:35.909 --> 25:38.452
They were a pile of books.
[Boy Laughing]

25:38.537 --> 25:41.372
That's a good one,
that is, squire.

25:41.456 --> 25:45.251
Pam, love,
it's not a bloody pile,
but it's a pile of books.

25:45.335 --> 25:47.711
- [All Laughing]
- All right. Settle down.

25:47.796 --> 25:53.217
- I was only tryin' to help,
Mr. Thackeray, sir.
- [Denham] That's right, Mr. Thackeray.

25:53.301 --> 25:56.220
Old Curly was only tryin'
to put the little scrubber
in her place.

25:56.304 --> 25:59.557
Denham!
I know what Curly
was trying to do!

25:59.641 --> 26:01.934
Now, just settle down.

26:03.353 --> 26:07.147
We are going to study
South America.

26:07.232 --> 26:12.486
Now, turn to page 37
in your geography book.

26:12.571 --> 26:15.489
[Chattering, Laughing]

26:51.651 --> 26:53.861
"...from whence
the honey sprung.

26:53.945 --> 26:56.280
They were alone
but not as alone as they...

26:56.364 --> 26:59.158
who shut in chambers
think it loneliness.

26:59.242 --> 27:02.786
The voiceless sand
and the drooping caves
that lay around them...

27:02.871 --> 27:07.291
made them to each other
press as if there were
no life beneath the sky...

27:07.375 --> 27:09.376
[Creaking]

27:09.461 --> 27:11.879
save theirs and that
their life could never—"

27:13.173 --> 27:16.216
Sorry, love.
It's the bleedin' desk.

27:16.301 --> 27:18.302
Do you use such words
when you're speaking to your father?

27:18.386 --> 27:20.054
You're not my bleedin' father!

27:22.140 --> 27:24.224
[School Bell Ringing]

27:24.309 --> 27:27.227
[Books Slamming Shut]

27:29.397 --> 27:33.192
[All Chattering]
[Girl] What I wanna know is,
who does he think he is?

27:37.739 --> 27:39.698
[Door Closes]

28:09.562 --> 28:12.481
[Ticking]

28:35.296 --> 28:37.256
[Students Chattering]
Shh!

28:37.340 --> 28:39.299
[Boy]
Hey, shut up! Shut up!
[Chattering Stops]

28:58.653 --> 29:01.655
Morning.
Morning.

29:02.741 --> 29:04.658
Hello, Thackeray.
Morning.

29:04.743 --> 29:07.661
How goes it?
Fine, thank you, sir.

29:09.456 --> 29:13.041
[Students Chattering]

29:13.126 --> 29:16.044
[Chattering Stops]

29:28.391 --> 29:31.018
All you boys, out!

29:31.102 --> 29:33.020
And the girls
stay where they are!

29:33.104 --> 29:35.272
- What's the matter,
Mr. Thackeray?
- Out!

29:35.356 --> 29:37.357
Out at once, before I‒

29:49.162 --> 29:51.955
I am sick of your foul language,

29:52.040 --> 29:55.375
your crude behavior
and your sluttish manner!

29:55.460 --> 29:58.003
There are certain things
a decent woman keeps private.

29:58.087 --> 30:00.631
And only a filthy slut
would have done this.

30:00.715 --> 30:02.800
And those who stood by
and encouraged her are just as bad.

30:02.884 --> 30:06.261
I don't care who's responsible!
You're all to blame!

30:06.346 --> 30:08.472
Now, I'm going to leave
this room for five minutes,
by which time...

30:08.556 --> 30:10.599
that disgusting object
had better be removed...

30:10.683 --> 30:13.644
and the windows opened
to clear away the stench!

30:13.728 --> 30:18.023
If you must play these filthy games,
do them in your homes...

30:18.107 --> 30:21.360
and not in my classroom.

30:32.580 --> 30:36.208
- Whatever is the matter?
- Man, oh, man.

30:38.086 --> 30:41.672
I lost my temper.
The one thing I swore
I would never, never do.

30:41.756 --> 30:44.675
God, did I lose my temper.
What happened?

30:44.759 --> 30:49.096
I never would have thought
after all of the bull
I've taken in my life‒

30:49.180 --> 30:52.099
In a few short weeks, those kids
have got me so steamed up...

30:52.183 --> 30:54.977
so‒ so easy, so quickly.

30:55.061 --> 30:56.979
I never would have thought it.

30:57.063 --> 30:58.981
Look, perhaps you're
trying too hard.

30:59.065 --> 31:01.400
Those kids
are devils incarnate, huh?

31:01.484 --> 31:05.237
I've tried everything.
Everything! But nothing I try...

31:06.072 --> 31:07.614
Kids.

31:07.699 --> 31:08.824
What?

31:08.908 --> 31:12.327
Kids. That's it.

31:14.122 --> 31:15.372
Kids.

31:16.708 --> 31:19.084
[Door Opens, Closes]

31:41.482 --> 31:44.067
Those are out.

31:44.152 --> 31:46.069
They are useless to you.

31:46.154 --> 31:48.071
I suddenly realized
that you are not children‒

31:48.156 --> 31:50.073
that you will be adults
in a few weeks,

31:50.158 --> 31:52.367
with all the responsibilities
that implies.

31:52.452 --> 31:56.788
So, from now on
you will be treated as such
by me and by each other‒

31:56.873 --> 32:00.584
as adults, responsible adults.

32:00.668 --> 32:04.171
Next, we are going to be
reasonable with each other.

32:04.255 --> 32:06.965
We are just going to talk, you and I.

32:07.050 --> 32:11.094
You are going to listen
without interruption,
and when I am finished,

32:11.179 --> 32:15.724
one of you may have your say
without interruptions.

32:15.808 --> 32:19.519
Next...
Oh, blimey,
what a morning I've had!

32:19.604 --> 32:21.521
First of all,
the bleeding alarm
didn't go off.

32:21.606 --> 32:24.524
Then I had to wait hours
for a bus.

32:24.609 --> 32:27.903
I must've stood there about
three hours waiting for a bus.
Example.

32:27.987 --> 32:30.572
There are two ways
to enter a room.

32:30.657 --> 32:34.868
One is like an adult,
a lady with dignity.
The other is like a brat.

32:34.953 --> 32:37.412
Miss Dare has just shown us
the second way.

32:37.497 --> 32:40.040
Perhaps you would care
to demonstrate the first.

33:09.779 --> 33:12.239
[Quietly]
I'm sorry I'm late.

33:13.616 --> 33:16.243
[Murmuring]

33:23.376 --> 33:29.006
Next, we are all going to observe
certain courtesies in this classroom.

33:29.090 --> 33:31.425
You will call me "sir"
or "Mr. Thackeray."

33:31.509 --> 33:34.302
The young ladies
will be addressed as "miss,"

33:34.387 --> 33:36.471
the boys by their surnames.

33:36.556 --> 33:38.932
Here, why should we
call 'em miss?
We know 'em.

33:39.017 --> 33:40.934
I beg your pardon?

33:41.019 --> 33:44.771
I said, "Why should we
call them miss, sir?
We know 'em."

33:44.856 --> 33:46.773
Is there anyone of these
young ladies you feel...

33:46.858 --> 33:50.444
does not deserve
to be addressed as miss?
[Chuckles]

33:58.494 --> 34:00.871
No, sir.
Good.

34:00.955 --> 34:03.331
Next, general deportment.

34:03.416 --> 34:05.375
First, the young ladies.

34:05.460 --> 34:07.502
They must prove that they
are worthy and appreciative...

34:07.587 --> 34:09.629
of the courtesies
we are going to show them.

34:09.714 --> 34:11.882
Soon boyfriends and marriage
will concern you.

34:11.966 --> 34:14.634
No man likes a slut for long.

34:14.719 --> 34:17.094
Only the worst type
will marry one.

34:18.473 --> 34:23.435
And the competition for men
on the outside is rough.

34:23.518 --> 34:26.103
Next, men.

34:26.188 --> 34:29.649
I've seen garbage collectors
who are cleaner.

34:31.319 --> 34:36.406
Toughness is a quality of the mind,
like bravery, honesty and ambition.

34:36.491 --> 34:39.034
If you want to wear
your hair long, clean it,

34:39.118 --> 34:42.829
else you will soon
get lice and smell.

34:42.914 --> 34:44.998
Soon your principal interest
will be girls.

34:45.083 --> 34:47.708
You will be
much more attractive to them
with clean clothes,

34:47.793 --> 34:51.295
clean shoes, hands, face,
teeth, et cetera.

34:51.380 --> 34:55.300
Now, any...
any questions?

34:58.054 --> 35:01.389
- Miss Pegg.
- What about Mr. Weston, sir?

35:01.474 --> 35:04.101
He's never tidy,
and his shoes is never brushed.

35:04.185 --> 35:06.770
And his hair's a mess, isn't it?
Yeah! It's filthy!

35:06.854 --> 35:10.690
[Students Chattering In Agreement]
Mr. Weston is not your teacher.
We won't discuss him.

35:11.776 --> 35:15.028
I'm the one to criticize
if I fail to maintain
the standards I ask of you.

35:15.113 --> 35:16.321
That's not fair.

35:19.450 --> 35:24.871
Sir... or Mr. Thackeray.
Didn't you understand?

35:24.956 --> 35:27.207
That's not fair,

35:27.291 --> 35:29.209
sir.

35:29.293 --> 35:32.504
I agree.
But that's just an example...

35:32.588 --> 35:34.965
of the many things you'll have
to put up with when you're an adult.

35:35.049 --> 35:37.592
You'll just have to take it.

35:39.220 --> 35:42.889
Next, we are going to talk
about various‒

35:43.724 --> 35:44.766
Oh.

35:46.060 --> 35:48.186
Good morning.
Good morning.

35:48.271 --> 35:51.356
I just wanted to see
how you were getting on.
Fine, thank you, sir.

35:51.440 --> 35:55.402
Good.
Well, thank you.

35:56.487 --> 35:59.406
[Chattering]

36:11.043 --> 36:12.961
What is it?

36:23.723 --> 36:25.640
Palmer.

36:25.725 --> 36:27.809
What are we gonna
talk about, sir?

36:30.313 --> 36:34.691
About life, survival,

36:34.775 --> 36:38.403
love, death, sex,

36:38.487 --> 36:40.530
marriage, rebellion,

36:40.615 --> 36:42.991
anything you want.

36:43.075 --> 36:45.994
[Murmuring]

36:47.455 --> 36:50.707
[Man On Record Player]
♪ No matter what you do ♪

36:50.791 --> 36:53.543
♪ No matter what you say ♪

36:53.628 --> 36:55.670
♪ I've had enough of you ♪

36:55.755 --> 36:59.883
- ♪ No matter what you do ♪
- I never did see one like him, Pam.

36:59.967 --> 37:03.637
Even when he blew his stack,
no swearin' or nothin'.

37:03.721 --> 37:06.640
Blimey.
Ain't natural, that's what.

37:06.724 --> 37:08.642
Does he really mean
what he says?

37:08.726 --> 37:11.311
I don't know.
It'd be a change,
though, wouldn't it?

37:11.395 --> 37:14.231
To see those creeps
acting like gents.
Yeah.

37:14.315 --> 37:17.525
Here, which one do you fancy?

37:17.610 --> 37:19.903
I like Babs.
Yeah?

37:19.987 --> 37:21.988
Watch this.

37:22.073 --> 37:23.740
Come on, Pam, luv.

37:23.824 --> 37:25.951
Aw, get lost Denham.

37:26.035 --> 37:28.411
I don't like your
smelly tricks, do I?

37:28.496 --> 37:30.580
And it's Miss Dare to you.

37:30.665 --> 37:33.959
Get stuffed.

37:36.754 --> 37:38.630
Come on, then, luv.

37:39.465 --> 37:43.760
You heard what sir said,
Mr. Smarty Denham!

37:43.844 --> 37:48.890
If you wanna dance with me,
you bleedin' well ask proper!

37:48.975 --> 37:50.934
[Laughter]

37:51.018 --> 37:55.563
Uh, may I have the pleasure
of this dance, Miss Pegg?
Blimey! Good old Potts!

37:55.648 --> 37:58.191
- Mmm, get you, Potter.
- Shut up!

37:58.276 --> 38:01.069
Who does he think he is,
bleedin' Fred Astaire?

38:01.153 --> 38:04.656
Yeah!
Come on, Miss Pegg.
[Laughter]

38:04.740 --> 38:06.700
♪ You took my love
for granted ♪

38:06.784 --> 38:11.329
- ♪ And you pushed your love too far ♪
- Oh, look at me.

38:11.414 --> 38:13.748
I am a lady, I am.

38:13.833 --> 38:15.875
[Laughter]

38:15.960 --> 38:19.129
♪ Just as far as I can go ♪

38:19.213 --> 38:22.924
♪ I've had it up to here
and I want out ♪

38:29.390 --> 38:31.641
♪ No matter what you do ♪

38:31.726 --> 38:34.269
♪ No matter what you say ♪

38:34.353 --> 38:36.730
♪ I've had enough of you ♪

38:36.814 --> 38:38.732
Rotten tarts, all of them.

38:38.816 --> 38:40.984
Bleedin' chimney sweep
was right about that.

38:41.068 --> 38:43.653
Well, you won't catch me
spending me nicker on them,
that's for sure.

38:43.738 --> 38:47.240
♪ I've had it up to here
and I want out ♪

38:47.325 --> 38:51.661
- Hey, he said we could talk
about anything, didn't he?
- You're so right, Tich, me old mate.

38:51.746 --> 38:54.831
He did say we could
ask him anything.
[Chuckles]

38:54.915 --> 38:56.833
Questions and answers, eh?

38:58.753 --> 39:00.670
♪ You took my love for granted ♪♪

39:02.631 --> 39:04.591
Yes, Denham.

39:06.093 --> 39:08.678
Uh, last night on the telly,
Mr. Thackeray,

39:08.763 --> 39:11.264
there was this, uh,
travelogue picture,
you know?

39:11.349 --> 39:15.268
A lot of black women
dancin' around with no tops on.

39:15.353 --> 39:19.522
- Don't they ever dress proper?
- What's proper varies
throughout the world,

39:19.607 --> 39:22.067
depending on customs and climate.

39:22.151 --> 39:25.820
For their climate
and according to their customs,
they were dressed properly.

39:25.905 --> 39:28.406
Are you from South Africa, sir?
Of course not.

39:28.491 --> 39:31.368
- South Africans is white, isn't they?
- [Laughter]

39:31.452 --> 39:35.246
A South African is a native of South Africa,
regardless of color.

39:35.331 --> 39:37.874
I was born in British Guiana.

39:37.958 --> 39:39.459
Yes, Ingham.

39:39.543 --> 39:44.047
Uh, what did you mean
the other day
about rebellion, sir?

39:44.131 --> 39:46.883
Change. Take your hairstyles.

39:46.967 --> 39:49.177
That's a form of rebellion, isn't it?

39:49.261 --> 39:51.179
Aye? What, sir?

39:51.263 --> 39:54.808
Don't you just do it to be
different from adults?
Isn't that the reason?

39:54.892 --> 39:56.935
Well, they've messed up
the world a bit, haven't they, sir?

39:57.019 --> 39:59.687
You can say that again.
So you rebel.

39:59.772 --> 40:03.733
Even the way you dress
is a form of rebellion, now, isn't it?

40:03.818 --> 40:05.777
Oh, it's just
the new fashion, sir.

40:05.861 --> 40:09.322
'Course, the adults
look proper stupid in our gear.

40:09.407 --> 40:13.201
Do you think it's wrong to change,
to be different, to rebel, sir?

40:13.285 --> 40:16.579
It is your duty
to change the world, if you can.

40:16.664 --> 40:21.418
Not by violence‒
peacefully, individually, not as a mob.

40:21.502 --> 40:25.088
Take the Beatles.
They started a huge social revolution.

40:25.172 --> 40:30.427
The fashions they set
in dress and hairstyles
are worldwide now.

40:30.511 --> 40:35.765
Every new fashion
is a form of rebellion.

40:35.850 --> 40:38.893
Now, there's
a fine exhibition of costumes
through the ages on...

40:38.978 --> 40:40.937
at the Victoria and Albert Museum.

40:41.021 --> 40:42.981
I think you
should go and see it.

40:43.065 --> 40:46.985
Also, you should stop in and see
the Museum of Natural History.
What?

40:47.069 --> 40:49.779
Us lot go to a museum?
Yeah.
Sure.

40:49.864 --> 40:51.906
You're jokin'.
You'll discover that
your hairstyles...

40:51.991 --> 40:54.951
are 200 years old...
[Chattering, Chuckling]

40:55.035 --> 41:00.206
and that your costumes
or your dress is, uh,
right out of 1920.

41:02.084 --> 41:04.252
Shut up! Look, sir,
when can we go?

41:04.336 --> 41:08.173
There's no time after school,
and I've got to look after
the kids and flat and all.

41:08.257 --> 41:11.759
Yeah, and I have to do
the housework and get the supper
for the lodgers and all, sir.

41:11.844 --> 41:15.555
Nor can I, sir. Me mum's
expectin' a baby any day,
and I got to babysit the others.

41:15.639 --> 41:18.933
Why don't you take us?
We could go in the morning.
Oh, yes!

41:19.018 --> 41:21.769
[Chattering In Agreement]
[Barbara]
I'd love that. Smashing!

41:21.854 --> 41:24.856
Who would like that?
[Chattering Continues]

41:26.567 --> 41:28.776
Oh, what a drag.
What's the matter?
Don't you want a day off?

41:28.861 --> 41:32.614
Put your hand up.
[Barbara]
Come on, Potts!

41:32.698 --> 41:35.492
Put both hands up.
Fat chance.

41:35.576 --> 41:39.954
It wouldn't work.
It's not the sort of risk
that we've ever dared...

41:40.039 --> 41:43.249
to take at North Quay.
I would like to try, sir.

41:43.334 --> 41:47.712
The best of pupils are
inclined to show off in public.

41:47.796 --> 41:49.297
Your class?

41:49.381 --> 41:52.342
You'd never be able
to supervise them.

41:53.844 --> 41:55.762
When I took this job, you said...

41:55.846 --> 41:58.848
that you wouldn't interfere
as long as I stayed
within your framework.

42:01.018 --> 42:02.936
Well, if you can persuade
another member of the staff...

42:03.020 --> 42:06.272
to go with you,
I'll approach the council.

42:06.357 --> 42:08.775
I see little hope of approval.

42:08.859 --> 42:10.777
Thank you, sir.

42:13.364 --> 42:15.448
[Heavy Vehicle Approaching]

42:25.584 --> 42:27.502
Miss Blanchard.

42:27.586 --> 42:30.797
Miss Blanchard, I-I think
I can arrange an outing
for my class...

42:30.881 --> 42:33.049
if I can get another
teacher to go along.

42:33.133 --> 42:35.426
I was‒
I'd love to. And it's Gillian.

42:35.511 --> 42:37.387
When is the outing, Mark?

42:37.471 --> 42:40.014
As soon as we can arrange
the travel warrants and permission.

42:40.099 --> 42:42.016
Well, just let me know when.
[Bell Dings]

42:42.101 --> 42:44.227
Thanks, Gillian. Bye.
Bye.

42:44.311 --> 42:46.271
[Students Chattering]

42:49.400 --> 42:52.986
Good morning.
[All]
Good morning, sir.

42:53.070 --> 42:55.905
What would you like
to talk about today?

42:58.742 --> 43:02.328
Ladies first. Miss Joseph.

43:02.413 --> 43:05.164
Marriage, sir.
You know, boyfriends
and things.

43:05.249 --> 43:07.166
How do you know
he's the right one?

43:07.251 --> 43:09.168
What do you think
a girl should look for?

43:09.253 --> 43:11.504
How to avoid
divorce, sir.
Don't get married!

43:11.589 --> 43:13.840
[Chattering, Laughing]

43:13.924 --> 43:17.218
Where's Miss Purcell?
She's to look after
the home today, sir.

43:17.303 --> 43:19.220
Her mum had the baby
last night.

43:19.305 --> 43:22.432
- Oh. What hospital?
- No hospital, sir.

43:22.516 --> 43:25.059
- The doctor came to her.
- She all right?

43:25.144 --> 43:27.729
Well, she just had a kid,
didn't she?

43:27.813 --> 43:30.690
[Chuckles]
Yeah.

43:30.774 --> 43:32.692
Well, now‒

43:32.776 --> 43:36.863
Marriage. First, let us lay
some ground rules.

43:36.947 --> 43:40.366
I've never been married,
so what I say is as an outsider.

43:40.451 --> 43:42.869
Now, what should a girl
look for in a man?

43:42.953 --> 43:46.914
I think first we ought
to determine what is marriage.

43:46.999 --> 43:48.458
Miss Joseph.

43:48.542 --> 43:52.128
Holy wedlock.
Holy wedlock?

43:52.212 --> 43:54.797
[Moira]
Potter, be serious.
You'll get your turn.

43:54.882 --> 43:58.217
Miss Pegg?
It's life, isn't it, sir?

43:58.302 --> 44:00.970
Everyone gets married.
I mean, sometime.

44:01.055 --> 44:02.972
Why didn't you get married, sir?

44:03.057 --> 44:06.559
[Potter]
No one would have him.
I was very poor.

44:06.644 --> 44:10.063
And there was something in me
that wanted an education,

44:10.147 --> 44:13.483
so I put all of my energies into that.

44:13.567 --> 44:16.235
And, well,
I got started later...

44:16.320 --> 44:19.155
and just never met
the right girl.

44:19.239 --> 44:21.324
Now, what should a girl
look for in a man?

44:21.408 --> 44:24.077
Miss Clark.
What work did you do, sir?

44:24.161 --> 44:26.079
I waited tables.

44:26.163 --> 44:28.581
I cooked in a hamburger joint.

44:28.666 --> 44:31.584
I washed dishes for a time. Cars.

44:31.669 --> 44:35.588
For a year I was a janitor
in an apartment block.
All sorts of jobs.

44:35.673 --> 44:37.840
You washed dishes, sir?
I did.

44:37.925 --> 44:40.426
- Yeah, but you talk posh and all.
- That wasn't easy.

44:40.511 --> 44:42.762
[Moira]
You didn't always talk like that, then?

44:42.846 --> 44:44.931
When I was your age
I used a patois‒

44:45.015 --> 44:47.016
a kind of simple English.

44:47.101 --> 44:50.770
[Rattling Off
Slang Phrases]
[Laughter]

44:50.854 --> 44:55.608
- Didn't understand a word, sir.
- Well, I don't always understand
what you say either.

44:55.693 --> 44:58.778
But the point is, if you're
prepared to work hard,
you can do almost anything.

44:58.862 --> 45:02.073
You can get any job you want.
You can even‒

45:03.158 --> 45:05.034
You can even, uh,

45:05.119 --> 45:08.454
change your speech,
if you want to.

45:08.539 --> 45:10.957
After I got my degree,
I went to work...

45:11.041 --> 45:12.959
in South America
for an oil company.

45:13.043 --> 45:14.961
The only women in that region...

45:15.045 --> 45:18.715
were jungle Indians
who carried blow pipes
and poison darts.

45:18.799 --> 45:20.717
[Laughter]

45:30.728 --> 45:32.645
You could have broke my hands.

45:35.733 --> 45:37.734
We were discussing marriage.

45:37.818 --> 45:41.988
To my mind, marriage
is no way of life for the weak,

45:42.072 --> 45:45.992
the selfish
or the insecure.

45:46.076 --> 45:47.994
[Groans]

45:48.078 --> 45:51.664
What's the matter, Weston?
These damned fool Americans.

45:51.749 --> 45:54.667
They bog up everything
they're connected with.

45:54.752 --> 45:56.669
What a shower.

45:56.754 --> 45:58.671
I'll never forgive
the president
for not coming...

45:58.756 --> 46:00.840
to dear old Churchill's funeral‒

46:00.924 --> 46:02.842
or at least sending
the vice president.

46:02.926 --> 46:05.511
Rotten bad manners.
It was very naughty.

46:05.596 --> 46:07.513
I quite agree.

46:07.598 --> 46:10.683
A typically
stupid, appalling
and unnecessary mistake.

46:10.768 --> 46:12.685
Still, what can you expect?

46:12.770 --> 46:14.854
Still beefing, Weston?
Give them a chance,
Mr. Weston.

46:14.938 --> 46:17.190
They have not been
in the business of
leading the world...

46:17.274 --> 46:21.527
as long as Britain was.
You continue
to astonish me, old chum.

46:21.612 --> 46:24.405
I should have thought
if anyone took a point of-
[Knocking]

46:24.490 --> 46:26.407
Oh, now what?

46:26.492 --> 46:28.409
Yes?
Excuse me, sir.

46:28.494 --> 46:30.411
Miss Pegg wants to know
if the net ball is fixed.

46:30.496 --> 46:33.998
Miss who?
Barbara Pegg.
Miss Pegg, sir.

46:34.082 --> 46:35.958
Here you are, Fernman.

46:36.043 --> 46:38.044
Thank you, sir.

46:38.128 --> 46:41.047
What's going on
in this classroom
of yours, old chum?

46:41.131 --> 46:45.051
Suburban formality?
It's a bit foreign in this
neck of the woods, isn't it?

46:45.135 --> 46:49.305
Some sort of experiment
in culture for the masses?

46:49.389 --> 46:51.390
It's an elementary
experiment in courtesy.

46:51.475 --> 46:55.061
And do we ignorant critters
have to follow suit?

46:55.145 --> 46:58.272
Please yourself.
Well, thank goodness for that.

46:58.357 --> 47:01.442
Do you object to being
taught manners by one
of the boys, Mr. Weston?

47:01.527 --> 47:03.945
I don't expect to be taught manners
by those morons.

47:04.029 --> 47:06.155
So long as we learn,
it doesn't matter
who teaches us, does it?

47:06.240 --> 47:08.783
Afternoon, everybody.

47:08.867 --> 47:11.244
[Weston]
Ah. Here's the man.

47:11.328 --> 47:15.581
Now, Weston.
Now we're talking.

47:15.666 --> 47:17.917
Thackeray.

47:18.001 --> 47:20.086
Clinty.
Nothing like payday.

47:20.170 --> 47:24.257
Oh, by the way.
Your museum visit
has been approved.

47:24.341 --> 47:26.592
But remember that
if anything goes wrong,
the whole school will suffer.

47:26.677 --> 47:29.428
Nothing will go wrong, sir.

47:29.513 --> 47:31.597
Gillian.
Thank you.

47:31.682 --> 47:35.017
Here you are,
Miss Phillips.
Miss Dawes.

47:35.102 --> 47:37.687
Here you are, Grace.

47:41.525 --> 47:43.442
[Bells Chiming]

48:08.552 --> 48:10.553
[Sniffles]

48:10.637 --> 48:13.723
[Laughs]
For a moment I thought
I was in the wrong classroom.

48:15.350 --> 48:18.144
Where's Jackson?
We don't know, sir.

48:18.228 --> 48:21.022
Old Tich wouldn't miss
nothing like this unless
he was sick or something.

48:21.106 --> 48:23.566
Well, we'll give him
a few minutes.

48:23.650 --> 48:25.610
[Chattering]

48:37.956 --> 48:39.874
It's me, sir, Jackson.

48:39.958 --> 48:42.710
I've got to take
the bag wash for me mum.
Can you wait a jiffy, please?

48:42.794 --> 48:45.379
Sure. How long will it take?

48:45.464 --> 48:48.090
Half a mo. It's just up the frog.
Lord love you, sir.

48:49.259 --> 48:51.886
Here, hang on, Tich.
I'll give you a hand.

48:57.517 --> 49:00.353
[Cheering, Laughing]

49:05.025 --> 49:08.194
All right, all right.
Back on the sidewalk.

49:12.950 --> 49:14.784
What's a frog
got to do with it?

49:14.868 --> 49:18.287
Oh, it's a rhyming slang, sir.
You know, old-fashioned
cockney.

49:18.372 --> 49:20.539
It's not used
anymore, sir.
Just for the old people.

49:20.624 --> 49:23.292
- Oh, it's a drag, sir.
- [Seales]
Frog means road, sir.

49:23.377 --> 49:25.586
- Frog and toad, road.
- Trouble and strife, wife.

49:25.671 --> 49:28.047
Weeping willow, pillow.
You just use the first word,
see?

49:28.131 --> 49:30.383
Like the old
currant bun, sir.
That's the sun.

49:30.467 --> 49:32.969
Apples and pears, stairs.
Happy kill, skill.

49:33.053 --> 49:35.888
[Laughing,
Chattering]

49:35.973 --> 49:38.724
Ginger beer, queer.
[Laughter]

49:38.809 --> 49:41.018
All right, all right.
All aboard.

49:50.696 --> 49:54.949
[Woman]
♪ Those schoolgirl days ♪

49:55.033 --> 49:58.911
♪ Of telling tales
and biting nails ♪

49:58.996 --> 50:01.747
♪ Are gone ♪

50:03.500 --> 50:07.253
♪ But in my mind ♪

50:07.337 --> 50:10.589
♪ I know they will still ♪

50:10.674 --> 50:15.678
♪ Live on and on ♪

50:15.762 --> 50:19.098
♪ But how do you thank someone ♪

50:19.182 --> 50:24.311
♪ Who's taken you
from crayons to perfume? ♪

50:24.396 --> 50:26.605
♪ It isn't easy ♪

50:26.690 --> 50:31.444
♪ But I'll try ♪

50:31.528 --> 50:33.529
♪ If you wanted the sky ♪

50:33.613 --> 50:35.656
♪ I would write across the sky ♪

50:35.741 --> 50:37.700
♪ In letters ♪

50:37.784 --> 50:41.996
♪ That would soar
a thousand feet high ♪

50:42.080 --> 50:44.206
♪ To sir ♪

50:44.291 --> 50:48.252
♪ With love ♪

50:49.838 --> 50:53.799
♪ Those awkward years ♪

50:53.884 --> 50:55.968
♪ Have hurried by ♪

50:56.053 --> 51:02.058
♪ Why did they fly away? ♪

51:02.142 --> 51:06.645
♪ Why is it, sir ♪

51:06.730 --> 51:08.814
♪ Children grow ♪

51:08.899 --> 51:13.903
♪ Up to be people one day? ♪

51:14.780 --> 51:17.823
♪ What takes the place
of climbing trees ♪

51:17.908 --> 51:23.162
♪ And dirty knees
in the world outside? ♪

51:23.246 --> 51:29.752
♪ What is there for you I can buy? ♪

51:29.836 --> 51:31.754
♪ If you wanted the world ♪

51:31.838 --> 51:34.465
♪ I'd surround it with a wall ♪

51:34.549 --> 51:37.051
♪ I'd scrawl ♪

51:37.135 --> 51:40.679
♪ These words with letters 10 feet tall ♪

51:40.764 --> 51:43.015
♪ To sir ♪

51:43.100 --> 51:46.435
♪ With love ♪♪

51:46.520 --> 51:49.063
[Both Laughing]

51:49.147 --> 51:51.148
I think he fancies her.

51:51.233 --> 51:53.109
I know you do.

51:53.193 --> 51:57.029
- Pamela Dare has quite a crush on you.
- Women say the damnedest things.

51:57.114 --> 52:00.741
I think he's nice.
So do I.

52:00.826 --> 52:04.286
- You've noticed, haven't you?
- I don't treat her any differently
from the other girls.

52:04.371 --> 52:07.873
I hope we can go out again,
don't you?
I hope so. It was fun.

52:07.958 --> 52:10.459
I hope we can go with him
because he's nice.
I like him.

52:10.544 --> 52:12.503
Don't make any mistake
about Pamela.

52:12.587 --> 52:14.713
She's a woman
in every sense of the word.

52:15.632 --> 52:18.259
I mean, not that I blame her.

52:20.846 --> 52:23.055
[Laughs]
Bleeding rotten taste he's got.

52:29.646 --> 52:32.815
[School Bell Ringing]

52:32.899 --> 52:34.859
[Laughing, Chattering]

52:41.867 --> 52:44.410
[Laughing, Chattering]

52:44.494 --> 52:46.412
Good night, sir.
Good night, sir.

52:46.496 --> 52:49.415
Good night, sir.
See you tomorrow,
Mr. Thackeray.

52:49.499 --> 52:52.084
Good night.
Good night, sir.

52:52.169 --> 52:54.253
Good night.
Good night, sir.

52:54.337 --> 52:57.590
Good night,
Mr. Thackeray.
Good night. Good night.

52:57.674 --> 53:00.259
Good night, sir.
Good night.

53:00.343 --> 53:03.095
Sir‒
[Door Closes]

53:03.180 --> 53:05.431
Perhaps you'd like me
to tidy your desk.

53:05.515 --> 53:07.433
Oh, well, no. That's all right.
No, it's all right.

53:07.517 --> 53:10.102
It's no trouble.
You know, you ought
to get a flat nearby.

53:10.187 --> 53:12.104
Brentwood's much too far away.
Yes, well‒

53:12.189 --> 53:14.607
There are some nice ones
around here.
I've thought of that.

53:14.691 --> 53:17.651
I'll tell you what.
I'll keep my ears open for you.

53:17.736 --> 53:20.613
That's very kind of you, Miss Dare,
but I'm fine for the moment.

53:20.697 --> 53:22.823
I'll let you know. Thank you.

53:23.909 --> 53:25.826
Don't worry
about your desk, sir.

53:25.911 --> 53:27.786
I'll tidy it for you every day.

53:27.871 --> 53:30.581
Thanks, but that...
that won't be necessary.

53:30.665 --> 53:32.583
That's perfectly all right.

53:32.667 --> 53:35.294
A woman's work is never done.

53:35.378 --> 53:37.922
Night, sir.

53:43.011 --> 53:44.511
[Door Closes]

53:49.476 --> 53:51.477
[Chattering, Laughing]

53:52.729 --> 53:54.813
Hi, fellas.
How are you?

53:54.898 --> 53:56.815
[Chattering]

54:00.070 --> 54:02.154
Good morning, sir.
Good morning.

54:02.239 --> 54:05.032
Mr. Florian has
given us permission
for more outings.

54:05.116 --> 54:07.034
Oh, that's great!
Great!

54:07.118 --> 54:09.036
I would like to hear
suggestions from you
of what we might do.

54:09.120 --> 54:11.038
Oh, the pictures, sir.
Wembley, sir.

54:11.122 --> 54:13.082
- Cup Final Day.
- Here, the Chamber of Horrors.

54:13.166 --> 54:15.084
Oh, that's a good one.
What about the Cavern?

54:15.168 --> 54:17.586
- Cavern?
- You know, sir,
Liverpool, The Beatles.

54:17.671 --> 54:19.755
How's it going, Fernman?

54:19.839 --> 54:23.509
- Fine, thank you, sir.
- Don't you worry about him, sir.
He'll come with me on my day.

54:23.593 --> 54:27.429
You're under a supervision
order too?
[Barbara] Around here that's nothing, sir.

54:27.514 --> 54:29.431
Most of us have been up
in front of the law.

54:29.516 --> 54:32.268
You know, breaking windows,
playing truant, raising hell...

54:32.352 --> 54:34.061
and cussing the coppers.

54:39.150 --> 54:41.777
Oh, you've cut yourself.
Oh, you'd better put
something on that, sir.

54:41.861 --> 54:43.779
You might get lockjaw
or something.

54:43.863 --> 54:48.826
- Blimey! Red blood!
- What do you expect, pinhead, ink?

54:52.372 --> 54:54.290
[Clatters]

54:54.374 --> 54:58.085
I didn't mean no harm, sir.
It was just a joke.
I didn't mean no crack, sir.

54:58.169 --> 55:00.087
It's all right.

55:06.052 --> 55:07.594
What's with you?

55:07.679 --> 55:10.264
Are you addressing me,
Denham?
Yeah.

55:10.348 --> 55:14.101
Potts was only being funny.
What'd you call him pinhead
for in front of chimney sweep?

55:14.185 --> 55:16.562
Going after Potts
in front of him?

55:16.646 --> 55:18.564
I was only having a little joke.
Sir didn't mind.

55:18.648 --> 55:21.317
- He said we could ask him
anything, didn't he?
- You call those questions?

55:21.401 --> 55:24.737
Always on about his color.
You've got nothing better
to talk about, have you?

55:24.821 --> 55:27.406
You're just wasting our time.
And, Seales, you ought
to know better.

55:27.490 --> 55:29.408
What have I done?
I didn't say nothing.

55:29.492 --> 55:32.161
No, you never say nothing.
And you're half-colored too.

55:32.245 --> 55:34.747
You sit on your fat ass
and keep your trap shut.

55:34.831 --> 55:36.832
If they want to know,
why don't they ask you?

55:36.916 --> 55:40.085
I'm not sir, that's why.

55:40.170 --> 55:42.087
I only wish I was.

55:49.929 --> 55:51.847
[Scoffs]

55:54.434 --> 55:58.645
I know what's eating you.
You fancy him, that's what.

56:01.733 --> 56:04.360
Well, this is a fine
how do you do, isn't it,
Potts, old mate?

56:04.444 --> 56:06.862
You lay off, Denham,
you son of-
[Train Passing]

56:13.370 --> 56:16.872
Today I'm going to show you
how to make a salad.

56:16.956 --> 56:18.957
You mean we've
to cook and all?

56:19.042 --> 56:20.959
[Clamoring]

56:21.044 --> 56:22.961
Sure. Why not?

56:23.046 --> 56:25.130
My old man never cooked
nothing in his whole life.

56:25.215 --> 56:27.716
He says that's woman's work,
the kitchen and all.

56:27.801 --> 56:29.760
Yeah.
Yeah.
Yeah.

56:29.844 --> 56:32.012
But suppose you're on your own,

56:32.097 --> 56:33.889
as you certainly will be shortly,

56:33.973 --> 56:36.475
then you'll have to do it
for yourselves sometimes,
won't you?

56:36.559 --> 56:38.477
[Murmuring]

56:39.896 --> 56:41.814
Oh, not again, sir.

56:41.898 --> 56:43.816
[Laughter]

56:43.900 --> 56:46.485
This is survival training.

56:46.569 --> 56:49.321
Now. Hmm?

56:51.408 --> 56:53.325
A normal English salad.

56:53.410 --> 56:56.662
Not fit for human consumption,
even if you remove the usual slugs...

56:56.746 --> 57:00.207
and add a dash
of the extraordinary...
a bit of mayonnaise.

57:00.291 --> 57:02.209
Now‒
[Door Opens]

57:02.293 --> 57:05.504
[Boy]
Look at her.
[Chattering]

57:10.427 --> 57:12.344
I'm sorry I'm late.

57:12.429 --> 57:14.596
Mum had to go to the doctor
and I didn't want
to miss the day, sir.

57:14.681 --> 57:16.598
He won't be no trouble.

57:16.683 --> 57:19.935
[Fussing]
[Thackeray]
It's all right.

57:20.019 --> 57:22.688
Sit down.
Make room over there.

57:22.772 --> 57:24.690
[Clamoring]

57:27.944 --> 57:29.862
Koochy-koochy-koochy.
All right, all right, Okay.

57:29.946 --> 57:32.364
Come on. Now‒

57:33.616 --> 57:35.701
Never be afraid
to experiment.

57:35.785 --> 57:39.371
And always remember
that you can eat well,
even though you're broke.

57:39.456 --> 57:41.457
See?
You ever been
broke, sir?

57:41.541 --> 57:43.876
Real broke? Skint?

57:45.545 --> 57:47.629
Yeah. Many, many, many times.

57:47.714 --> 57:49.715
Oh, I don't
understand you a bit, sir.

57:49.799 --> 57:52.968
I mean, you're a toff...
and you ain't.

57:53.052 --> 57:55.554
Huh?
Sir?

57:55.638 --> 57:59.057
What he means is‒
Well, blimey.

57:59.142 --> 58:02.728
I can't sort of
put it into words
or anything, but...

58:02.812 --> 58:06.231
Well, sir, you're like us,
but you ain't.

58:06.316 --> 58:10.068
I mean, you're not.
It's kind of scary, but nice.

58:10.153 --> 58:12.279
You know what I mean,
don't you?

58:13.990 --> 58:16.867
Well, I‒ I don't know how
to answer you, except to say...

58:16.951 --> 58:20.204
that I teach you truths‒
my truths.

58:20.288 --> 58:23.582
Yeah, it is kind of scary,
dealing with the truth.

58:24.626 --> 58:26.919
Scary and dangerous.

58:29.172 --> 58:32.424
Now, have you ever
had a salad with, uh,

58:32.509 --> 58:35.427
with almonds and grapes
and tomatoes...

58:35.512 --> 58:37.429
and lettuce
and pineapple?

58:37.514 --> 58:40.599
[Students Clamoring,
Chattering]

58:40.683 --> 58:42.601
She's obviously
in love with you, Mark.

58:42.685 --> 58:46.271
[Laughs]
Oh, you shouldn't
be so surprised.

58:46.356 --> 58:49.107
We have a lot
of marvelous schools now
in the East End.

58:49.192 --> 58:52.110
It's still difficult
to get quality teachers.

58:52.195 --> 58:55.113
Take us‒
the bottom of the pile.

58:55.198 --> 58:58.450
Goodness knows we've
had a scruffy lot here.

58:58.535 --> 59:01.620
Then along comes
Mr. Mark Thackeray...

59:01.704 --> 59:05.123
big, broad, handsome,
clean, intelligent,

59:05.208 --> 59:08.794
looking like he stepped
out of a bandbox.

59:08.878 --> 59:10.963
What do you expect?

59:11.047 --> 59:12.965
What do I do?

59:13.049 --> 59:16.802
Nothing.
Just be patient.

59:16.886 --> 59:18.428
Thanks.

59:19.889 --> 59:24.142
Pamela's just finding out
she's a grown woman.

59:24.227 --> 59:28.814
You're probably
the only real man
she's ever met in her life.

59:28.898 --> 59:30.983
Don't spend too much time
alone with her.

59:33.236 --> 59:35.153
Why didn't you ask Gillian?

59:37.907 --> 59:40.659
Oh, I thought you'd be wiser.

59:40.743 --> 59:43.161
[Sighs]

59:43.246 --> 59:45.163
Well, thanks.

59:48.710 --> 59:50.627
[Door Closes]

01:00:15.445 --> 01:00:17.529
Well, hello, sir.

01:00:17.614 --> 01:00:19.531
We can't have you
queuing up.

01:00:19.616 --> 01:00:22.534
It's sir.
He teaches our Moira
up at North Quay.

01:00:22.619 --> 01:00:25.037
He's only got an hour
for his lunch,
that's all he's got.

01:00:25.121 --> 01:00:27.122
Now, what'll it be, sir?
Half a dozen oranges.

01:00:27.206 --> 01:00:29.875
Oh, you'll like them.
They're lovely and juicy.

01:00:29.959 --> 01:00:32.753
Here you are, guv.
Penny's wedding cake.

01:00:32.837 --> 01:00:35.464
Jeanie's elder sister.
She went and got
married,

01:00:35.548 --> 01:00:38.216
so we thought we'd give you
a bit of cake for luck.

01:00:38.301 --> 01:00:42.220
Jeanie Clark.
Oh! Yes. Miss Clark.

01:00:42.305 --> 01:00:45.390
That was a lovely museum
outing they went on.
We'll have to do it again.

01:00:45.475 --> 01:00:47.809
The Museum? Oh, well,

01:00:47.894 --> 01:00:50.145
we're trying to arrange
one a week.

01:00:50.229 --> 01:00:52.230
Oh, that'll be lovely,
won't it, Horace?

01:00:52.315 --> 01:00:55.984
The more education
they learns, the better.
That's what I always say.

01:00:56.069 --> 01:00:59.613
It's a proper bleeder, you know,
what with the bomb and all.

01:00:59.697 --> 01:01:02.824
'Tain't the bombs.
It's them bleedin'
foreigners, them Yanks.

01:01:02.909 --> 01:01:06.578
Shut your gob.
My Gert's married to a Yank.

01:01:06.663 --> 01:01:08.622
And a proper
nice gent he is, and all.

01:01:08.706 --> 01:01:10.832
I'll thank you to keep
your opinions to yourself.

01:01:10.917 --> 01:01:14.795
God Al-bloody-mighty.
Getting technical, eh?

01:01:14.879 --> 01:01:17.255
Listen, first cast the mote
out of your own bleedin' eye...

01:01:17.340 --> 01:01:19.257
before you cast the bomb
out of mine.
Aw, shut up.

01:01:19.342 --> 01:01:21.259
He's a proper faggot.
Here you are.

01:01:21.344 --> 01:01:23.261
You'll like them, sir.
Thank you.

01:01:23.346 --> 01:01:25.597
Thank you.
Who's next?
Come on, girls.

01:01:25.682 --> 01:01:27.599
Speak up.

01:01:30.687 --> 01:01:33.105
Gillian?
Uh-huh?

01:01:33.189 --> 01:01:37.109
I was wondering if you
would also give the girls
some lessons in makeup.

01:01:39.362 --> 01:01:42.614
I think quite a few
of them would be, uh,

01:01:42.699 --> 01:01:45.701
very pretty
if they knew how to do it.

01:01:45.785 --> 01:01:47.744
Well, certainly.

01:01:53.042 --> 01:01:55.794
You really are
getting involved
with your children,

01:01:55.878 --> 01:01:58.088
aren't you?
No, I'm just trying to help.

01:01:58.172 --> 01:02:00.048
That's the job, isn't it?

01:02:00.133 --> 01:02:02.134
You want some of this?
No, thanks.

01:02:02.218 --> 01:02:04.970
Is that all you're
having for lunch?
Yep.

01:02:05.054 --> 01:02:10.559
You on a diet?
No. I'll tell you‒
I'm a weak man.

01:02:10.643 --> 01:02:12.811
At the moment, a little skint.

01:02:12.895 --> 01:02:14.813
When I eat,
[Slurps]
do I love to eat.

01:02:14.897 --> 01:02:18.483
[Laughs]
And I love wine,
but I just can't have a glass.

01:02:18.568 --> 01:02:20.569
I want to drink
the whole bottle.

01:02:20.653 --> 01:02:23.405
So I avoid wine
and pastrami sandwiches...

01:02:23.489 --> 01:02:25.490
and baked potatoes...

01:02:25.575 --> 01:02:29.161
with butter and bacon...

01:02:29.245 --> 01:02:31.872
and strawberry shortcake
and cheesecake.

01:02:31.956 --> 01:02:33.874
[Laughing]

01:02:37.086 --> 01:02:39.421
But I like to eat light,
uh, for lunch.

01:02:42.717 --> 01:02:44.634
How is it
with the Dare girl?

01:02:48.514 --> 01:02:50.432
No problems.

01:02:51.934 --> 01:02:55.103
Are you going
to stay on here, Mark?
Until I get sorted out.

01:02:55.188 --> 01:02:57.147
No luck with the job?

01:02:57.231 --> 01:02:59.191
But I'm plugging away.

01:03:01.277 --> 01:03:04.905
Remember a few weeks ago,
when you thought you'd
lost the battle?

01:03:06.532 --> 01:03:10.660
I thought you had too.
There's a good angel
looking after me somewhere.

01:03:14.791 --> 01:03:16.875
Come on.
Sort yourselves out.

01:03:18.961 --> 01:03:20.879
Go on. Hurry up.

01:03:22.632 --> 01:03:24.883
All right, go.

01:03:24.967 --> 01:03:27.052
Come on, Denham.
Hurry it up.

01:03:31.140 --> 01:03:34.059
Land on your toes.
Do it again. Next.

01:03:36.229 --> 01:03:37.854
Next!

01:03:39.565 --> 01:03:43.568
Next! Buckley!

01:03:43.653 --> 01:03:45.570
Come on, boy.
I'm not a boy.

01:03:45.655 --> 01:03:47.405
I'm a man, and I don't want
to do it, sir.

01:03:47.490 --> 01:03:50.033
- It's too high.
- You're a boy,
and you're a fat boy too.

01:03:50.117 --> 01:03:52.577
Come on. I'm waiting.
Get some of that jelly off of you.

01:03:52.662 --> 01:03:54.788
Fats can't do it.
It's too high for him.

01:03:54.872 --> 01:03:56.790
'Course he can't do it.

01:03:59.335 --> 01:04:01.336
When I want your opinion,
I'll ask for it, boy.

01:04:01.420 --> 01:04:03.630
I'm not a boy.
Shut up!

01:04:06.509 --> 01:04:08.802
Buckley, do as you're told.

01:04:10.847 --> 01:04:12.639
Come on.

01:04:21.774 --> 01:04:24.109
[Groans]

01:04:26.696 --> 01:04:28.780
[Moaning]

01:04:31.200 --> 01:04:33.660
Move out of the way, boy!
Shut up!

01:04:34.954 --> 01:04:36.997
[Buckley Moaning]
Is he all right, Bert?

01:04:37.081 --> 01:04:39.249
[Moaning]
I don't know.

01:04:45.423 --> 01:04:47.340
You bloody bastard.

01:04:47.425 --> 01:04:49.885
Put that down, Potter!
You knew Fats
couldn't do that.

01:04:49.969 --> 01:04:51.887
You've always
had it in for him.

01:04:51.971 --> 01:04:53.889
Potter, put that down.

01:04:58.853 --> 01:05:00.854
Quick, sir!
They're fighting
in the gym, sir!

01:05:03.065 --> 01:05:05.483
Go on, Potts!

01:05:08.613 --> 01:05:10.530
- For the last time, put it down!
- That weren't no accident!

01:05:10.615 --> 01:05:12.532
Potter!

01:05:14.744 --> 01:05:16.661
I'll take that.

01:05:21.083 --> 01:05:23.668
Go and help Buckley.
Go on.

01:05:28.424 --> 01:05:30.842
Potts should have done
the bastard
like he did Fats.

01:05:43.940 --> 01:05:46.191
You all right, boy?
Yes, thank you, sir.

01:05:46.275 --> 01:05:48.193
Me stomach doesn't
half hurt though.

01:05:48.277 --> 01:05:51.029
Jackson, Ingham,
help him up to Mrs. Evans.

01:05:56.118 --> 01:05:58.453
All right.

01:05:58.537 --> 01:06:00.538
What happened?

01:06:00.623 --> 01:06:04.084
[Sighs]
Hmm?

01:06:15.304 --> 01:06:16.846
Buckley's all right.

01:06:17.974 --> 01:06:20.225
More frightened
than anything else.

01:06:22.478 --> 01:06:24.562
Why'd you make him
do that jump?

01:06:25.648 --> 01:06:27.565
He just stood there
and refused to obey.

01:06:27.650 --> 01:06:32.237
When he jumped,
well, he sent the buck flying
and I couldn't catch him.

01:06:32.321 --> 01:06:34.239
Oh.

01:06:34.323 --> 01:06:37.575
Thanks for helping me out.
That Potter went berserk.

01:06:39.662 --> 01:06:41.579
[Sighs]

01:06:42.665 --> 01:06:44.749
I understand
that Buckley is a...

01:06:44.834 --> 01:06:46.751
pet whipping boy of yours.

01:06:46.836 --> 01:06:48.753
Is that right?

01:06:48.838 --> 01:06:52.757
I'd better report it to the head.
There's gonna be the devil to pay.

01:07:06.063 --> 01:07:07.981
[Chattering]

01:07:23.539 --> 01:07:27.167
Potter? I can't think of anything
that could excuse your behavior.

01:07:27.251 --> 01:07:30.295
But it was him, sir!
He made Fats do it!

01:07:30.379 --> 01:07:34.007
Fats said he couldn't do it!
The bloody bully has always
had it in for him!

01:07:34.091 --> 01:07:36.801
I'm not concerned with
Mr. Bell's behavior, but yours.

01:07:36.886 --> 01:07:39.554
Suppose instead of a piece
of wood, a gun or a knife
had been handy, eh?

01:07:39.638 --> 01:07:42.307
What then?
Potter was narked.
We was all narked.

01:07:42.391 --> 01:07:44.434
That bleeder was in the wrong,
and you bloody well know it.

01:07:44.518 --> 01:07:47.312
You're missing the point, Denham.
You all are.

01:07:47.396 --> 01:07:49.731
In a few weeks you will
be going out into the world.

01:07:49.815 --> 01:07:52.400
Are you going to use
a weapon every time
someone makes you angry?

01:07:52.485 --> 01:07:55.820
You're supposed to be learning
self-discipline here.

01:07:55.905 --> 01:07:58.865
Potter, you owe Mr. Bell
an apology.

01:07:58.949 --> 01:08:01.659
Huh?
No!
[All Shouting]

01:08:01.744 --> 01:08:05.830
Why should he apologize?
Just 'cause Bell's
a bleedin' teacher, eh?

01:08:05.915 --> 01:08:07.999
You'd better
answer that, Potter.

01:08:08.084 --> 01:08:10.543
Do you think you behaved
like a‒ like an adult?

01:08:22.765 --> 01:08:24.765
How about Bell apologizing
to Buckley, eh?

01:08:25.935 --> 01:08:28.812
My business is with you,
not Mr. Bell.

01:08:28.895 --> 01:08:30.772
It's easy for you
to talk.

01:08:30.856 --> 01:08:33.274
No one pushes you around.

01:08:33.359 --> 01:08:35.693
Well, Potter?

01:08:35.778 --> 01:08:38.404
Are you a man or a hoodlum?

01:08:42.451 --> 01:08:44.368
Do it, Potts.
Do it?
Denham!

01:08:44.453 --> 01:08:46.371
[All Talking]

01:08:46.455 --> 01:08:48.372
Bell will put you up
before the law
if you don't, won't he?

01:08:48.457 --> 01:08:51.376
And you've got to have
recommends for a job,
ain't you?

01:08:51.460 --> 01:08:53.627
He's got to sign one,
hasn't he?

01:08:53.712 --> 01:08:57.549
This has nothing to do
with what I sign or won't sign.

01:08:57.633 --> 01:08:59.884
There's never been
a teacher you could trust.

01:08:59.969 --> 01:09:02.804
We're only safe together...
against them.
Like it's always been.

01:09:02.888 --> 01:09:06.224
But sir's different!
If he says Potts is‒
That he is.

01:09:06.308 --> 01:09:08.017
And he's wrong now.

01:09:09.145 --> 01:09:12.104
You all know Bell's been
after old Fats for years.

01:09:16.819 --> 01:09:18.736
Go on, Potts.

01:09:28.330 --> 01:09:31.249
If you apologize
because you're afraid,

01:09:31.332 --> 01:09:34.419
then you're a child, not a man.

01:09:40.259 --> 01:09:42.260
[Door Closes]

01:09:43.679 --> 01:09:48.515
When I leave, I've me own bearer,
so you can't touch me,

01:09:48.600 --> 01:09:50.560
letters or no letters.

01:10:11.874 --> 01:10:13.791
I'm sorry I'm late, sir.

01:10:16.045 --> 01:10:17.962
But it's me mum, sir.

01:10:19.715 --> 01:10:21.633
She's dead.

01:10:23.219 --> 01:10:25.637
I've been helping
me dad with her things.

01:10:30.226 --> 01:10:32.810
[Voice Breaking]
I didn't... I didn't...
I didn't know where to go, sir.

01:10:32.895 --> 01:10:35.146
It's all right.
[Sobbing]

01:10:35.231 --> 01:10:37.857
Ingham, take over the class.

01:10:59.588 --> 01:11:02.006
I understand that
the passing out class...

01:11:02.091 --> 01:11:06.344
holds some kind
of a celebration
at the end of term.

01:11:06.428 --> 01:11:08.346
What happens?

01:11:10.599 --> 01:11:12.517
Hmm?

01:11:12.601 --> 01:11:15.270
Hmm?
We dance,

01:11:15.354 --> 01:11:17.855
sir.

01:11:20.442 --> 01:11:22.568
Did you apologize because
of what Denham said?

01:11:27.283 --> 01:11:29.617
I believe one should fight
for what one believes,

01:11:29.702 --> 01:11:33.496
provided one
is absolutely sure...

01:11:33.580 --> 01:11:36.040
one is absolutely right.

01:11:37.626 --> 01:11:39.544
Pass these out.

01:11:50.306 --> 01:11:52.765
You have to fill those out.

01:11:52.850 --> 01:11:54.767
For national health
insurance...

01:11:54.852 --> 01:11:56.769
and so on.

01:12:07.990 --> 01:12:09.907
[Chattering]

01:12:24.673 --> 01:12:27.091
What are you doing, Jackson?

01:12:27.176 --> 01:12:29.594
It's for Seales, sir.
For flowers and a wreath.

01:12:29.678 --> 01:12:33.931
That's-That's
wonderful of you.

01:12:34.016 --> 01:12:36.768
May I be permitted
to contribute something?

01:12:36.852 --> 01:12:39.103
No, thank you, Mr. Thackeray.

01:12:41.357 --> 01:12:43.983
Here, Pam, luv.
You buy the wreath, eh?

01:12:44.068 --> 01:12:46.444
The name's Dare.
Miss Dare.

01:12:46.528 --> 01:12:48.780
Yeah, well,
you buy the wreath.

01:12:48.864 --> 01:12:51.449
Send it round
when the time's right.

01:12:52.868 --> 01:12:55.119
Send it?
Aren't you going to take it?

01:13:00.709 --> 01:13:03.294
You don't think the girls
could take it, do you?

01:13:03.379 --> 01:13:05.755
Well, why not?

01:13:18.477 --> 01:13:20.311
[Moira]
Well‒

01:13:20.396 --> 01:13:23.981
Well, it's what people
would say, sir.

01:13:24.066 --> 01:13:26.776
What the family'd say...

01:13:26.860 --> 01:13:29.237
if they saw us going
into a colored person's home, sir.

01:13:31.323 --> 01:13:33.366
[Barbara]
We've got nothing
against you, sir.

01:13:33.450 --> 01:13:35.368
Honest.

01:13:35.452 --> 01:13:37.662
But if one of us was‒

01:13:37.746 --> 01:13:40.164
Well, you can't imagine
the things that'd be said, sir.

01:13:48.090 --> 01:13:50.007
Well.

01:13:51.927 --> 01:13:53.845
[Laughs]

01:13:59.726 --> 01:14:01.102
Well‒

01:14:06.900 --> 01:14:10.736
Thank you, Miss Pegg,
for making it clear.

01:14:12.531 --> 01:14:17.285
Well, does that apply
to the men also?

01:14:17.369 --> 01:14:19.871
You're dead right it does.

01:14:28.797 --> 01:14:30.715
I'll take the flowers, sir.

01:14:34.219 --> 01:14:36.888
Why should you do that,
Miss Dare?

01:14:36.972 --> 01:14:39.223
Wouldn't that make you
subject to gossip?

01:14:39.308 --> 01:14:41.225
Gossip don't worry me.

01:14:41.310 --> 01:14:44.228
I've known Seales since
we were in kindergarten.

01:14:44.313 --> 01:14:46.772
I'll take the flowers.

01:14:46.857 --> 01:14:49.567
I wouldn't, if I were you.

01:15:12.633 --> 01:15:14.550
Ah, Thackeray.

01:15:14.635 --> 01:15:16.511
I've been looking for you.

01:15:16.595 --> 01:15:19.430
There's a lady to see you‒
Mrs. Dare.

01:15:21.099 --> 01:15:25.436
By the way, I've canceled
all outings for your class.

01:15:25.521 --> 01:15:27.480
Why?

01:15:27.564 --> 01:15:29.857
I'm afraid the adult
approach hasn't worked.

01:15:29.942 --> 01:15:32.818
It would have been better
to let things be.

01:15:32.903 --> 01:15:36.614
You'd better take your boys for PT
until I get a replacement.

01:15:44.581 --> 01:15:45.915
[Door Opens]

01:15:47.376 --> 01:15:48.543
Oh.

01:15:49.753 --> 01:15:52.129
I-I'm sorry to disturb you, sir.

01:15:52.214 --> 01:15:55.466
It's about Pam.
I'm Mrs. Dare.

01:15:55.551 --> 01:15:57.468
What can I do for you,
Mrs. Dare?

01:15:57.553 --> 01:16:00.555
Would you have a seat?
W-Would you talk
to her, sir?

01:16:00.639 --> 01:16:02.557
I'm sure she'd listen to you.

01:16:02.641 --> 01:16:05.017
She's always
talking about you.
What's the problem?

01:16:06.103 --> 01:16:08.312
Well‒

01:16:08.397 --> 01:16:10.648
She always stays
out late at night, sir.

01:16:10.732 --> 01:16:14.485
Often she doesn't get home
till past 11:00.

01:16:14.570 --> 01:16:16.654
She never says where she's been.

01:16:16.738 --> 01:16:19.740
She's a big girl, sir.
I'm worried about her.

01:16:19.825 --> 01:16:21.742
She won't listen to me.

01:16:23.370 --> 01:16:25.329
Well, I'm just a teacher, Mrs. Dare.

01:16:25.414 --> 01:16:27.331
Oh, I know she'd
listen to you, sir.

01:16:27.416 --> 01:16:30.501
When her friends are over,
it's always, "sir said this"
or "sir said that."

01:16:30.586 --> 01:16:34.005
See, she‒ she won't listen to me, sir.

01:16:34.089 --> 01:16:36.507
She‒ She just won't.

01:16:36.592 --> 01:16:38.884
Why doesn't her father
have a talk with her?

01:16:39.845 --> 01:16:42.179
Oh. Oh, no.

01:16:42.264 --> 01:16:44.682
No, we're divorced. H-He's uh‒
He's up north somewhere.

01:16:44.766 --> 01:16:46.267
He doesn't...

01:16:47.853 --> 01:16:51.188
Well, it's not wrong to‒

01:16:53.108 --> 01:16:56.193
I mean, when your marriage breaks up,
your life doesn't end, does it?

01:16:57.446 --> 01:17:00.531
Please talk to her, sir.
I'm frightened for her.

01:17:00.616 --> 01:17:04.702
You never know what sort
of trouble she can get into.

01:17:06.121 --> 01:17:08.039
Please.

01:17:10.459 --> 01:17:12.752
All right. I will.

01:17:12.836 --> 01:17:14.879
Thank you.

01:17:16.840 --> 01:17:19.550
[Door Opens, Closes]

01:18:13.939 --> 01:18:15.856
Morning, sir.

01:18:15.941 --> 01:18:17.858
[Crowd Chattering]
[Woman]
Hello, love.

01:18:17.943 --> 01:18:19.860
[Man] Morning, Mr. Thackeray.
[Man #1]
How are you. How's the kids?

01:18:19.945 --> 01:18:22.113
Hello, guv.

01:18:23.782 --> 01:18:26.283
Hello, sir.
It's a lovely day, ain't it?

01:18:26.368 --> 01:18:28.494
Your kid ain't top of the class.

01:18:28.578 --> 01:18:30.496
Who's got everything?

01:18:45.887 --> 01:18:50.141
Mark! Hi! Hi!

01:18:50.225 --> 01:18:52.309
Hi.
You look as if
you'd won the pools.

01:18:52.394 --> 01:18:54.311
Oh, better.
Whoop!

01:18:54.396 --> 01:18:57.481
I got me a job‒ a real one‒
when school ends.

01:18:57.566 --> 01:19:00.651
Third assistant engineer
in a radio factory in the midlands.

01:19:00.736 --> 01:19:04.321
They even sent me the fare.
Oh, that's marvelous.

01:19:04.406 --> 01:19:07.491
Well, it's not that good,
but it's a start after so long.

01:19:07.576 --> 01:19:11.162
Think she's gonna take
those flowers, Bert?

01:19:11.246 --> 01:19:13.497
I don't know.

01:19:13.582 --> 01:19:15.499
Hey, Pam!

01:19:15.584 --> 01:19:17.501
Hey, sir wants you.

01:19:24.009 --> 01:19:26.302
[Door Opens]

01:19:32.267 --> 01:19:35.352
Sit down, Miss Dare.
I'd like to talk to you.

01:19:35.437 --> 01:19:37.855
Has my mum been in?
Yes.

01:19:41.109 --> 01:19:44.361
The funeral
is Saturday, 10:30.

01:19:47.949 --> 01:19:52.203
About my mum, sir?
She's very worried
about you, Miss Dare.

01:19:53.455 --> 01:19:55.372
Couldn't you
call me Pamela?

01:19:57.626 --> 01:20:00.044
I think not, for the moment.

01:20:00.128 --> 01:20:03.047
She says that you've
been staying out late.

01:20:03.131 --> 01:20:05.049
Oh, I've just been
round to Gran's.

01:20:05.133 --> 01:20:07.718
It's just round the corner.
It's not far.

01:20:08.804 --> 01:20:10.721
Why haven't you told
your mother then?

01:20:10.806 --> 01:20:12.723
Because she doesn't
care about me.

01:20:12.808 --> 01:20:15.184
Well, now,
you know that's not true.

01:20:18.355 --> 01:20:20.272
You're not in trouble, are you?

01:20:20.357 --> 01:20:22.566
[Scoffs]
Oh, no, sir.

01:20:22.651 --> 01:20:25.736
Nowadays that's only
for fools, isn't it?

01:20:25.821 --> 01:20:27.905
We're the luckiest bunch of kids,

01:20:27.989 --> 01:20:30.658
the luckiest generation
that's ever been, aren't we?

01:20:30.742 --> 01:20:32.785
We're the first to be really free...

01:20:32.869 --> 01:20:35.746
to enjoy life, if we want,

01:20:35.831 --> 01:20:37.748
without fear.

01:20:38.917 --> 01:20:40.501
Well, what is the trouble?

01:20:40.585 --> 01:20:44.171
Look, if you don't want to talk,
just say the word.

01:20:44.256 --> 01:20:47.424
It doesn't bother me.

01:20:47.509 --> 01:20:50.761
Well, it was all right
up until about a year ago.

01:20:50.846 --> 01:20:52.763
Of course I miss Dad.
H-He was wonderful.

01:20:52.848 --> 01:20:56.100
But... it's just one
of those things, isn't it?

01:20:58.353 --> 01:21:01.438
Mum works up in a dress shop
up in the West End,

01:21:01.523 --> 01:21:03.440
and we got on fine.

01:21:05.193 --> 01:21:07.611
Then men friends
started calling on her.

01:21:09.030 --> 01:21:11.448
Well, you know
what neighbors are like.

01:21:13.201 --> 01:21:16.120
That's all, really.
There's nothing else to tell.

01:21:17.747 --> 01:21:19.665
She doesn't like me.

01:21:19.749 --> 01:21:21.959
I'm in the way.

01:21:22.043 --> 01:21:24.962
Well, she's young and pretty,
isn't she?

01:21:25.046 --> 01:21:27.756
I shall be glad when I can
leave school and be on my own.

01:21:29.384 --> 01:21:31.802
Obviously, your mother loves you,

01:21:31.887 --> 01:21:34.388
and you owe her much more
than any teacher.

01:21:34.472 --> 01:21:36.974
I think you're wrong
about her.

01:21:37.058 --> 01:21:41.312
Did she tell you that I found her
with one of her friends?

01:21:41.396 --> 01:21:44.481
At home? At my home?

01:21:44.566 --> 01:21:47.192
No, I bet she didn't,
but she was.

01:21:47.277 --> 01:21:50.529
All families have problems.
I can't solve that for you.

01:21:50.614 --> 01:21:52.531
But staying out late won't help.

01:21:52.616 --> 01:21:54.992
Well, it helps me.
I can't stand the sight of her,

01:21:55.076 --> 01:21:57.995
and if you were me,
you'd feel the same.

01:21:58.079 --> 01:21:59.997
I'm in no position to judge.

01:22:00.081 --> 01:22:03.167
- I know that people make mistakes.
- Are you saying it's my fault?

01:22:03.251 --> 01:22:05.169
I'm saying that forgiveness
is the gift of God‒

01:22:05.253 --> 01:22:08.547
that people make mistakes‒
that it's up to you to make
peace with your mother.

01:22:08.632 --> 01:22:12.426
Why should I?
I haven't done anything.
Grow up, Miss Dare.

01:22:12.510 --> 01:22:14.678
It's up to you to give her
another chance.

01:22:14.763 --> 01:22:17.389
I told you what she did.
Why are you taking her side?

01:22:17.474 --> 01:22:20.184
Because you're wrong
not to give her a second chance.

01:22:20.268 --> 01:22:22.770
Everybody deserves that.

01:22:24.022 --> 01:22:25.940
I thought you'd understand.
I thought you were different.

01:22:26.024 --> 01:22:27.942
I thought I could trust you.

01:22:28.026 --> 01:22:29.944
But you're just as Denham said.

01:22:30.028 --> 01:22:32.112
Well, I'm not taking
the bloody flowers!

01:23:25.166 --> 01:23:27.084
All right.

01:23:28.837 --> 01:23:31.005
Let's line up here in the center.

01:23:31.089 --> 01:23:33.924
Could we have boxing
first today, please,
Mr. Thackeray?

01:23:34.009 --> 01:23:36.427
[All Shouting Agreement]

01:23:36.511 --> 01:23:38.512
- Why?
- Well, it'd make a change.

01:23:40.348 --> 01:23:44.101
Okay. Just sort yourselves
into pairs now.

01:23:44.185 --> 01:23:46.311
Uh, do you mind
having a go with me,
Mr. Thackeray?

01:23:46.396 --> 01:23:50.149
Sapiano's hurt his wrist.
That's right, sir.
Sprained it,

01:23:50.233 --> 01:23:52.151
didn't I?

01:23:54.529 --> 01:23:56.947
I think you, uh, ought to wait...

01:23:57.032 --> 01:23:58.949
and have a go at Potter
or one of the others
when they're finished.

01:23:59.034 --> 01:24:01.785
Cor, he'll be done in, sir.

01:24:01.870 --> 01:24:04.788
Go on. I don't mind having
a punch-up with you.

01:24:09.210 --> 01:24:12.296
I think you'd better
forget that for today.

01:24:12.380 --> 01:24:14.298
Let's go.

01:24:27.896 --> 01:24:29.813
[Sighs]

01:24:29.898 --> 01:24:31.982
Okay.

01:24:32.067 --> 01:24:33.984
Let's go.

01:24:50.585 --> 01:24:52.503
[Students Shouting]

01:25:14.609 --> 01:25:17.152
[All Shouting]

01:25:28.998 --> 01:25:30.624
Come on!

01:25:39.717 --> 01:25:41.760
[Groaning]

01:25:46.141 --> 01:25:48.058
Stay where you are.

01:25:48.143 --> 01:25:50.060
[Groaning Continues]

01:25:51.646 --> 01:25:53.147
Put your head down.

01:25:54.315 --> 01:25:59.069
Potter, Gypsy, collect the gloves.
and put them back in the box.

01:25:59.154 --> 01:26:01.905
The rest of you line up over here
for vaulting.

01:26:04.826 --> 01:26:06.743
Put your head down.

01:26:08.163 --> 01:26:10.080
[Denham Groans]

01:26:10.165 --> 01:26:13.083
Are you all right?
Yeah.

01:26:13.168 --> 01:26:15.252
Come on over here
for a minute.
I'm all right, sir.

01:26:22.010 --> 01:26:23.927
Think I'll go wash up.

01:26:28.016 --> 01:26:29.516
Sh‒

01:26:34.522 --> 01:26:36.732
You all right, mate?
Yes. Yes.

01:26:36.816 --> 01:26:38.775
[Chattering]

01:26:40.695 --> 01:26:42.613
[School Bell Ringing]
[Laughing, Chattering]

01:26:48.870 --> 01:26:51.121
Can I ask you something?
Sure.

01:26:51.206 --> 01:26:53.790
How many times
did you hit me?
Once.

01:26:53.875 --> 01:26:56.460
I'm sorry about that.
I didn't mean to hurt you.

01:26:56.544 --> 01:26:58.462
I just lost my temper.

01:26:58.546 --> 01:27:00.464
I was meaning to hurt you.

01:27:00.548 --> 01:27:03.133
Well, you did. You're pretty good.

01:27:03.218 --> 01:27:05.302
Yeah, well, why didn't you
hit me again, eh?

01:27:05.386 --> 01:27:07.971
